hook.real_world_problem:
BookMyShow releases 1,000 concert tickets. Within milliseconds, 5,000 users click 'Book'. Without locking:

```java
// THE BUG — runs concurrently on 5000 threads:
@Transactional
public BookingResult bookTicket(String eventId, String userId) {
    Event event = eventRepo.findById(eventId).orElseThrow();

    if (event.getAvailableTickets() <= 0) {
        return BookingResult.SOLD_OUT;
    }

    // RACE CONDITION: two threads both read 1 ticket available!
    // Thread A: reads available=1, proceeds
    // Thread B: reads available=1, proceeds — at the SAME time!

    event.setAvailableTickets(event.getAvailableTickets() - 1);
    // Thread A saves: available=0
    // Thread B saves: available=0 (OVERWRITES Thread A!)
    // Both bookings succeed — 2 people hold the same ticket!

    return BookingResult.success(createBooking(event, userId));
}
// Result: 1000 tickets sold 2× = 2000 bookings! Chaos!
```

**Fix with Optimistic Locking:**
```java
@Entity class Event {
    @Id Long id;
    @Version int version;  // ← auto-incremented by Hibernate
    int availableTickets;
}

// Thread A: UPDATE events SET available=0, version=2 WHERE id=? AND version=1  → 1 row
// Thread B: UPDATE events SET available=0, version=2 WHERE id=? AND version=1  → 0 rows!
// Thread B gets OptimisticLockException → BookMyShow retries or shows 'Sold Out'
```

**Fix with Pessimistic Locking (SELECT FOR UPDATE):**
```java
@Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
Optional<Event> findByIdForUpdate(Long id);

// Thread A: SELECT ... FOR UPDATE → acquires row lock
// Thread B: SELECT ... FOR UPDATE → WAITS until Thread A commits
// Serialized: Thread A books, Thread B then checks (0 tickets) → Sold Out
```

Locking is the difference between 'it works in testing' and 'it works at 5000 concurrent users'.

concept_explanation.optimistic_locking:
**Optimistic Locking — @Version:**

```java
@Entity @Table(name = "tickets")
public class Ticket {
    @Id @GeneratedValue(strategy = GenerationType.IDENTITY)
    private Long id;

    private String eventId;
    private int available;

    @Version
    private int version;   // ← Hibernate manages this automatically

    // @Version: Hibernate adds 'AND version = ?' to every UPDATE
    // UPDATE tickets SET available=?, version=? WHERE id=? AND version=?
    // If 0 rows updated → another transaction already changed this row
    // → Hibernate throws OptimisticLockException!
}

// Service using optimistic locking:
@Service
public class TicketService {
    private final TicketRepository repo;

    @Retryable(
        value = OptimisticLockException.class,
        maxAttempts = 3,
        backoff = @Backoff(delay = 100)
    )
    @Transactional
    public BookingResult book(Long ticketId, String userId) {
        Ticket ticket = repo.findById(ticketId).orElseThrow();

        if (ticket.getAvailable() <= 0) {
            return BookingResult.SOLD_OUT;
        }

        ticket.setAvailable(ticket.getAvailable() - 1);
        repo.save(ticket);
        // Hibernate: UPDATE tickets SET available=N-1, version=V+1
        //            WHERE id=? AND version=V
        // If another transaction won: 0 rows updated → OptimisticLockException
        // @Retryable: retries up to 3 times automatically

        return BookingResult.success(createBooking(ticket, userId));
    }
}
```

**When @Version fails (conflict detection):**
```
Thread A: reads version=1, available=1
Thread B: reads version=1, available=1
Thread A: UPDATE ... version=2 WHERE version=1 → 1 row updated ✓
Thread B: UPDATE ... version=2 WHERE version=1 → 0 rows updated!
          → StaleObjectStateException (wraps OptimisticLockException)
          → Retry: re-read ticket → version=2, available=0 → SOLD_OUT
```

concept_explanation.pessimistic_locking:
**Pessimistic Locking — @Lock / SELECT FOR UPDATE:**

```java
import org.springframework.data.jpa.repository.Lock;
import jakarta.persistence.LockModeType;

// In Repository:
public interface TicketRepository extends JpaRepository<Ticket, Long> {

    // PESSIMISTIC_WRITE: SELECT ... FOR UPDATE
    // Other transactions trying to SELECT FOR UPDATE will WAIT
    @Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
    @Query("SELECT t FROM Ticket t WHERE t.id = :id")
    Optional<Ticket> findByIdWithLock(@Param("id") Long id);

    // PESSIMISTIC_READ: SELECT ... FOR SHARE
    // Allows other reads, blocks writes
    @Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_READ)
    Optional<Ticket> findById(Long id);  // override default

    // With timeout (don't wait more than 3 seconds):
    @Lock(LockModeType.PESSIMISTIC_WRITE)
    @QueryHints(@QueryHint(name="jakarta.persistence.lock.timeout", value="3000"))
    @Query("SELECT t FROM Ticket t WHERE t.id = :id")
    Optional<Ticket> findByIdWithLockTimeout(@Param("id") Long id);
}

// Service using pessimistic locking:
@Transactional
public BookingResult bookWithPessimisticLock(Long ticketId, String userId) {
    // Acquire lock BEFORE reading:
    Ticket ticket = repo.findByIdWithLock(ticketId).orElseThrow();
    // SQL: SELECT * FROM tickets WHERE id=? FOR UPDATE
    // Other threads trying to SELECT FOR UPDATE will block here!

    if (ticket.getAvailable() <= 0) return BookingResult.SOLD_OUT;
    ticket.setAvailable(ticket.getAvailable() - 1);
    // On transaction commit: lock released, waiting threads unblock
    return BookingResult.success(createBooking(ticket, userId));
}
```

concept_explanation.transactional_propagation:
**@Transactional propagation — nested transactions:**

```java
// Propagation.REQUIRED (default): join existing transaction or create new
@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRED)
public void processOrder(Order order) {
    // If called from within a transaction: joins it
    // If called standalone: creates new transaction
    orderRepo.save(order);  // participates in same transaction as caller
}

// Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW: always create NEW transaction (suspends current)
@Transactional(propagation = Propagation.REQUIRES_NEW)
public void sendNotification(String userId, String message) {
    // Always runs in its own transaction
    // If the OUTER transaction rolls back, this STILL commits!
    notificationRepo.save(new Notification(userId, message));
}
// USE CASE: audit log that must be saved even if order fails
@Transactional
public void placeOrder(Order order) {
    try {
        orderService.save(order);      // in main transaction
        paymentService.charge(order);  // in main transaction
    } catch (Exception e) {
        auditService.logFailure(order); // in NEW transaction (still commits!)
        throw e;                        // main transaction rolls back
    }
}

// rollbackFor: @Transactional only rolls back on RuntimeException by default!
@Transactional(rollbackFor = Exception.class)  // roll back on ANY exception
public void saveAndNotify() throws Exception {
    repo.save(entity);
    emailService.send();  // throws checked IOException → ROLLED BACK with this setting
}
// Without rollbackFor: checked exception doesn't roll back → entity saved, email failed!
```

